`IFormFile` buffers the entire body into memory by default. Instead, read the raw request body stream and write it to disk in chunks:

**1. Disable the form body size limit and request buffering:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
{
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});
```

**2. Stream directly to disk in your endpoint:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Ensure it's multipart
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) != null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            || !cd.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize!
        var path = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        await using var stream = File.Create(path);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(stream);  // streams in 80KB chunks
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**3. Disable form value count/size limits on the endpoint:**

```csharp
app.MapPost("/upload", ...)
   .DisableAntiforgery()
   .WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());
```

**Key points:**

- `MultipartReader` reads sections one at a time from the network stream — nothing is buffered in memory.
- `CopyToAsync` uses an internal 80 KB buffer by default (you can pass a larger one for throughput).
- Never use `IFormFile` or `Request.Form` — both trigger full buffering.
- Add `[RequestFormLimits(MultipartBodyLengthLimit = ...)]` or the equivalent metadata if you're hitting the 128 MB default multipart limit.

**Required using:**
```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;
```

This pattern keeps memory flat regardless of file size.
